  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-16 mb-4">How to Prepare for Your First Business English Lesson</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6 leading-relaxed">To get the most out of your investment, you should not go into a lesson without a plan. Here is how to prepare:</p>
  <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-600 mb-8">
    <li><strong>Identify your "Pain Points":</strong> Are you struggling with emails? Do you freeze during Q&A sessions? Tell your tutor exactly what you find difficult.</li>
    <li><strong>Bring Real Materials:</strong> If you have a presentation coming up, bring the slides. If you have a report to write, bring the draft. Working on real-world tasks is the fastest way to learn.</li>
    <li><strong>Record Your Lessons:</strong> Most platforms allow you to record sessions. Watching yourself back can be painful, but it is the best way to spot recurring mistakes in your speech.</li>
    <li><strong>Set Micro-Goals:</strong> Instead of saying "I want to be fluent," say "I want to be able to lead a 10-minute status update without looking at my notes."</li>
  </ol>

